{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a08dc128-6a38-4f26-ac9e-dd949a3d0645","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK moved forward → workloads need to catch up → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try:\n```bash\ndotnet workload update --from-previous-sdk\n```\nThis carries forward workloads that were installed under your previous SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e64aa3c0-5453-4502-aebd-a2e687d4cced","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any code.","outputTokens":252,"requestId":"1116:3766FA:BF2F27:DF29DC:69FE8500"},"id":"17302c6b-be61-4557-bbc5-018c83d88c64","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:51:21.132Z","parentId":"071fb5da-43cf-4152-ac9b-005c8d459d83"}
